  "prompt": "How has legislation evolved to combat money laundering?",
  "response": "Legislation combating money laundering has evolved significantly over the past few decades:\n\n1. Early Developments\n- Bank Secrecy Act (1970, US)\n- First international anti-money laundering guidelines\n- Initial focus on drug-related financial crimes\n\n2. Key Milestones\n- Financial Action Task Force (FATF) established in 1989\n- Increased international cooperation\n- Development of standardized compliance frameworks\n\n3. Major Legislative Enhancements\n- USA PATRIOT Act (2001)\n- Enhanced reporting requirements\n- Expanded financial institution obligations\n- Stricter customer identification procedures\n\n4. Global Compliance Standards\n- Know Your Customer (KYC) regulations\n- Customer due diligence requirements\n- Suspicious transaction reporting mandates\n\n5. Technological Adaptations\n- Regulations addressing cryptocurrency transactions\n- Digital platform monitoring\n- Advanced transaction tracking technologies\n\n6. Recent Trends\n- Increased penalties for non-compliance\n- More comprehensive risk assessment frameworks\n- Greater emphasis on beneficial ownership transparency\n\n7. Emerging Focus Areas\n- Combating terrorist financing\n- Addressing complex international financial networks\n- Blockchain and cryptocurrency regulations\n\nThe legislative landscape continues to evolve, adapting to increasingly sophisticated financial crime techniques.",
